{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Required patient fields (name, date of birth, insurance ID) are validated before any downstream processing; missing fields return a clear error listing all missing items.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is orchestration plus validation: a unit test can verify missing-field detection, but can miss accidental downstream calls. Integration is needed to assert both complete error aggregation and that insurance/triage/scheduling are not invoked.","test_description":"Run intake through the real intake service wiring with an input missing multiple required fields. Assert response contains all missing fields in one error and assert no downstream side effects (no payer call, no triage call, no schedule row, no confirmation).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Date of birth validation rejects future dates, dates more than 150 years ago, and non-date strings.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic rule logic on direct inputs/outputs; no I/O or cross-module boundary is required to reproduce real failures.","test_description":"Test DOB validator function with boundary dates and malformed strings: tomorrow, 151-years-ago date, valid 150-years-ago boundary, and non-date tokens. Assert exact validation outcomes/messages.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Insurance eligibility check sends correct patient ID and plan code to payer API and interprets eligible/not eligible/pending responses.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real HTTP contract errors (serialization, headers, endpoint shape) can be hidden by in-process mocks. Minimum robust boundary is real HTTP request/response handling 